      {
        "content": "Emma: Sure, Ms. Johnson. The water cycle has several stages: evaporation, condensation, precipitation, and collection. Evaporation is when water from oceans, lakes, or rivers turns into vapor because of the sun's heat. Condensation is when the water vapor cools and forms clouds. Precipitation occurs when clouds get heavy and water falls back to Earth as rain, snow, or sleet. Collection is when the water gathers in bodies of water, and the cycle repeats.\n\nLiam: Thanks, Emma. So, climate change can impact the evaporation stage. As temperatures rise, more water can evaporate from the Earth's surface, potentially leading to changes in precipitation patterns. This might cause more intense rainfall in some areas and droughts in others.\n\nAlex: Ms. Johnson, is it possible for climate change to affect how clouds form during the condensation stage as well?",
